"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-andy-murray-confirms-retirement-paris-olympics-01j3ft1fpmn9\", \"text\": \"Three-time Grand Slam champion Andy Murray confirmed on Tuesday he will retire from tennis after the Paris Olympics.  Murray, 37, played inhis final Wimbledon tournamentearlier this month, losing in the first round of the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s doubles competition. He previously withdrew from the Wimbledon singles competition due to his ongoing recovery from a spinal cyst procedure on June 22.  Murray, who will compete in both the singles and doubles tournaments in Paris this summer, posted an emotional message on X ahead of the Olympics:  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cArrived in Paris for my last ever tennis tournament,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Murray wrote. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cCompeting for Team GB has been by far the most memorable weeks of my career and I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m extremely proud to get to do it one final time!\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Arrived in Paris for my last ever tennis tournament@OlympicsCompeting for \\u00f0\\u009f\\u0087\\u00ac\\u00f0\\u009f\\u0087\\u00a7 have been by far the most memorable weeks of my career and I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m extremely proud to get do it one final time!pic.twitter.com/keqnpvSEE1  Murray\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s decorated 19-year career will come to an end after what will be his fifth Olympics appearance, having debuted in the 2008 tournament in Beijing. The draw for the Paris games is slated to take place on Thursday. Along with the singles tournament, Murray will compete in the doubles competition alongside compatriot Dan Evans, who is currently ranked world No. 59 by ATP.  Murray is a two-time Olympic gold medalist, winning back-to-back titles at London 2012\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094where he memorably beat Roger Federer in a straight-sets victory\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and Rio 2016.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m ready to finish playing,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Murray said at his last Wimbledon tournament. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t want that to be the case. I would love to play, like I said, forever\\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 If I knew my body was going to be able to do it, I would play \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s nothing about the sport that I hate and I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m like, I don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t want to do it anymore for this reason. I like the traveling. I love the competition, practicing, trying to get better, all those things. I know that it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s time now.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Kristen Wong is a staff writer on the Breaking and Trending News team at Sports Illustrated. She has been a sports journalist since 2020 and has a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in English and linguistics from Columbia University. Before joining SI in November 2023, Wong covered four NFL teams as an associate editor with the FanSided NFL network and worked as a staff writer for the brand\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s flagship site. She is a lifelong Liverpool fan who enjoys solving crossword puzzles and hanging out at her neighborhood dive bar in NYC.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"